00:00:00,120 --> 00:00:05,560
If you stay, I’ll reveal the best 
smart money concepts guide on Youtube!
  

2
00:00:05,560 --> 00:00:11,960
Let’s start with the order flow. Order flow 
refers to the external swing points of the market. 

3
00:00:11,960 --> 00:00:16,520
These are the key turning points 
where price changes direction. 

4
00:00:16,520 --> 00:00:22,120
To identify these swing points, you need 
to zoom out and look at the bigger picture. 

5
00:00:22,120 --> 00:00:26,600
Start by picking a higher time frame.
Now, mark out the significant  

6
00:00:26,600 --> 00:00:32,120
highs and lows on that chart.
These are your external structure points.
  

7
00:00:32,120 --> 00:00:38,760
If you see that price is making lower highs 
and lower lows, then the order flow is bearish. 

8
00:00:38,760 --> 00:00:44,080
This means that the big players in the 
market, are actively pushing price down. 
  

9
00:00:44,080 --> 00:00:51,320
If you see price making a series of higher highs 
and higher lows, then the order flow is bullish. 

10
00:00:51,320 --> 00:00:57,400
In this case, the smart money are accumulating 
positions and driving the market up.
  

11
00:00:57,400 --> 00:01:01,920
Now, these big players don't just 
buy and sell randomly. They have  

12
00:01:01,920 --> 00:01:07,200
specific intentions and goals in mind.
This is where the concept of order flow  

13
00:01:07,200 --> 00:01:13,560
comes in. By analyzing the external swing points, 
you can read the overall direction of the market.
  

14
00:01:13,560 --> 00:01:17,440
The key is to trade in the same 
direction as the order flow. 

15
00:01:17,440 --> 00:01:23,760
Don't try to fight the trend or guess when the 
market will turn. Instead, focus on following the  

16
00:01:23,760 --> 00:01:30,800
big players and riding the big waves they create.
 
Now, one of the best ways to analyze order flow  

17
00:01:30,800 --> 00:01:35,560
is to look at multiple time frames.
Each time frame gives you a different  

18
00:01:35,560 --> 00:01:39,040
perspective on the market.
The higher time frames show you  

19
00:01:39,040 --> 00:01:44,320
the bigger picture, while the lower 
time frames show you the details.
  

20
00:01:44,320 --> 00:01:48,680
The external swing points on a 
lower time frame are often seen as  

21
00:01:48,680 --> 00:01:54,600
internal structure on a higher time frame.
This is why it's so important to look at  

22
00:01:54,600 --> 00:02:00,600
multiple time frames when you read the market.
 
For example, you might start by looking at the  

23
00:02:00,600 --> 00:02:08,160
4-hour chart to get a sense of the overall trend.
If you see a series of lower highs and lower lows,  

24
00:02:08,160 --> 00:02:13,040
you know the order flow is bearish. 
 
Then, you can drop down to the 15-minute  

25
00:02:13,040 --> 00:02:18,920
chart to look for specific entry points.
On the 15-minute chart, you'll see smaller  

26
00:02:18,920 --> 00:02:25,120
swings that are part of the bigger picture.
These are called internal structure points.  

27
00:02:25,120 --> 00:02:31,720
They're the building blocks of the larger trend.
 
Thus, by comparing the 15-minute swings to the  

28
00:02:31,720 --> 00:02:38,280
4-hour trend, you can get a sense of how 
the market is behaving on a smaller scale. 

29
00:02:38,280 --> 00:02:44,520
You then simply look for bearish setups on the 
15-minute chart that align with the overall  

30
00:02:44,520 --> 00:02:48,560
bearish order flow on the 4-hour chart.
 
Trend 

31
00:02:48,560 --> 00:02:53,200
Trend is all about the direction 
of price over a specific period.  

32
00:02:53,200 --> 00:02:58,840
It's the overall movement of the market.
To identify the trend, you need to focus on  

33
00:02:58,840 --> 00:03:04,960
the internal swing points, on a lower time frame.
Internal swing points are the smaller highs and  

34
00:03:04,960 --> 00:03:10,440
lows that occur within a larger trend. 
 
If you see that price is making a series  

35
00:03:10,440 --> 00:03:15,480
of higher highs and higher lows, 
then the trend is currently bullish. 

36
00:03:15,480 --> 00:03:22,480
Each new high is higher than the previous one, and 
each new low is also higher than the one before. 

37
00:03:22,480 --> 00:03:28,520
In a bullish trend, you'll often see strong, 
impulsive moves to the upside followed by  

38
00:03:28,520 --> 00:03:34,520
smaller, corrective moves to the downside.
These corrections are typically short-lived  

39
00:03:34,520 --> 00:03:40,040
and serve as opportunities for buyers 
to enter the market at a better price.
  

40
00:03:40,040 --> 00:03:44,440
On the flip side, if price is 
making a series of lower highs  

41
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:50,840
and lower lows, then the trend is bearish.
In a bearish trend, you'll often see strong,  

42
00:03:50,840 --> 00:03:57,400
impulsive moves to the downside followed 
by smaller, corrective moves to the upside. 

43
00:03:57,400 --> 00:04:02,920
These corrections are typically short-lived and 
serve as opportunities for sellers to enter the  

44
00:04:02,920 --> 00:04:05,720
market at a better price.
 
 
Fractal Alignment 

45
00:04:05,720 --> 00:04:11,960
Now let’s talk about Fractal Alignment and how 
it ties together the order flow and the trend. 

46
00:04:11,960 --> 00:04:18,080
So, order flow is the overall direction of the 
market, determined by the external swing points,  

47
00:04:18,080 --> 00:04:24,600
the big picture view of where price is heading.
Trend is the current phase of that direction,  

48
00:04:24,600 --> 00:04:30,840
identified by the internal swing points. It's 
like zooming in on a specific part of the chart.
  

49
00:04:30,840 --> 00:04:35,560
Remember this: the internal direction 
(the trend) actually makes up the  

50
00:04:35,560 --> 00:04:40,960
external direction (the order flow).
It's like a fractal pattern, where the  

51
00:04:40,960 --> 00:04:46,720
smaller parts contribute to the larger whole.
 
To really understand this relationship,  

52
00:04:46,720 --> 00:04:52,200
you need to assess order flow and trend 
in relation to each other. This is where  

53
00:04:52,200 --> 00:04:57,960
multi-timeframe analysis comes into play.
By looking at different time frames, you can  

54
00:04:57,960 --> 00:05:05,480
see how the trend on a lower time frame fits into 
the overall order flow on a higher time frame.
  

55
00:05:05,480 --> 00:05:12,440
Let's say the order flow on the daily chart 
is bearish, making lower lows and lower highs. 

56
00:05:12,440 --> 00:05:18,120
However, when we zoom in to the 1-hour chart, 
we see that the current trend is actually  

57
00:05:18,120 --> 00:05:23,480
making higher highs and higher lows.
This is a common scenario that occurs  

58
00:05:23,480 --> 00:05:29,280
when the order flow is pulling back. 
 
After a new low or high is established,  

59
00:05:29,280 --> 00:05:33,880
price will often gravitate to collect 
more orders before continuing in  

60
00:05:33,880 --> 00:05:39,640
the direction of the overall order flow.
During this process, the trend on the lower time  

61
00:05:39,640 --> 00:05:45,480
frame may differ from the higher time frame.
As price navigates towards your points of  

62
00:05:45,480 --> 00:05:51,640
interest, you need to wait for trend and order 
flow to align before entering the market. 
  

63
00:05:51,640 --> 00:05:55,920
So it's all about looking for 
consistency between the time frames. 

64
00:05:55,920 --> 00:06:02,120
If the order flow on the daily chart is bearish, 
we want to see the trend on the 1-hour chart  

65
00:06:02,120 --> 00:06:09,040
also making lower lows and lower highs. 
 
If the trend on the 4-hour chart is bullish,  

66
00:06:09,040 --> 00:06:16,000
you want to see the order flow on the 15 minute 
chart also making higher highs and higher lows. 

67
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:22,862
When trend and order flow are aligned, the market 
is more likely to continue in that direction.
  

68
00:06:22,862 --> 00:06:24,000
Break of Structure
The next smart money  

69
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:28,360
concept is the break of structure.
Looking at this price chart,  

70
00:06:28,360 --> 00:06:34,760
you see a series of swing highs and swing lows.
When price breaks above the most recent swing  

71
00:06:34,760 --> 00:06:40,040
high and closes above it, this is a 
Break of Structure to the upside.
  

72
00:06:40,040 --> 00:06:46,440
It means that the old structure, which was defined 
by the previous swing high, has been broken. 

73
00:06:46,440 --> 00:06:52,200
Price has now created a new structure, 
with a new swing high in place.
  

74
00:06:52,200 --> 00:06:58,320
The same concept applies to the downside. If 
price breaks and closes below a swing low,  

75
00:06:58,320 --> 00:07:03,360
it's a Break of Structure to the downside.
The old structure has been broken,  

76
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:07,920
and a new one has been created.
 
A Break of Structure is viewed as a  

77
00:07:07,920 --> 00:07:14,720
continuation sign. It tells you that the buyers 
or sellers have taken control, and that price is  

78
00:07:14,720 --> 00:07:21,440
likely to continue in the direction of the break.
So, to make it very clear, a Break of Structure  

79
00:07:21,440 --> 00:07:27,800
is simply a break above a previous higher 
high in an uptrend, or a break below a lower  

80
00:07:27,800 --> 00:07:30,960
low in a downtrend.
 
Change of Character 

81
00:07:30,960 --> 00:07:34,600
The Change of Character is 
another important concept. 

82
00:07:34,600 --> 00:07:38,520
You’re looking at this price chart, 
and you see a market that has been  

83
00:07:38,520 --> 00:07:45,680
in a downtrend for some time. Price has been 
steadily making lower highs and lower lows. 

84
00:07:45,680 --> 00:07:51,040
And then price suddenly breaks above 
the previous major swing high. 
  

85
00:07:51,040 --> 00:07:56,960
This is a significant event, because it means that 
the buyers have finally gained the upper hand. 

86
00:07:56,960 --> 00:08:00,800
They've managed to push price 
above a key level of resistance,  

87
00:08:00,800 --> 00:08:07,480
and this could signal a potential trend reversal.
This is what we call a Change of Character. It's a  

88
00:08:07,480 --> 00:08:13,240
sudden and significant shift in the price action 
of the market. In this case, the change is from  

89
00:08:13,240 --> 00:08:20,040
a bearish trend to a potentially bullish one.
 
 
The key is to watch what happens next. If price  

90
00:08:20,040 --> 00:08:25,920
continues to make new higher highs and higher 
lows, then we can say with confidence that  

91
00:08:25,920 --> 00:08:31,280
we've transitioned into an uptrend. 
 
In an uptrend, a Change of Character  

92
00:08:31,280 --> 00:08:37,280
would be signaled by a break below a previous 
major swing low. This would indicate that the  

93
00:08:37,280 --> 00:08:42,760
sellers have taken control, and that the 
trend may be reversing to the downside.
  

94
00:08:42,760 --> 00:08:48,600
If price continues to make new lower lows 
and lower highs, then we can say that we've  

95
00:08:48,600 --> 00:08:51,320
transitioned into a downtrend.
 
Premium /Discount 

96
00:08:51,320 --> 00:08:56,720
The Premium and Discount zones are 
VERY important in smart money trading. 

97
00:08:56,720 --> 00:09:02,160
In this chart, the distance between a 
swing high and a swing low is called  

98
00:09:02,160 --> 00:09:06,200
a price swing, or a price wave.
If you to measure the distance  

99
00:09:06,200 --> 00:09:11,360
from the top of the leg to the bottom 
and you apply a Fibonacci retracement,  

100
00:09:11,360 --> 00:09:17,600
you can get the Premium and Discount range.
 
In general, anything above the 50% mark of  

101
00:09:17,600 --> 00:09:22,600
the price swing can be considered 
Premium, while anything below the  

102
00:09:22,600 --> 00:09:28,720
50% mark can be considered Discount. 
 
When price is trading in the Premium area,  

103
00:09:28,720 --> 00:09:33,800
it's like gravity is pulling it back down.
There's a higher probability that price  

104
00:09:33,800 --> 00:09:38,760
will reverse and start moving lower.
This means that selling in the Premium  

105
00:09:38,760 --> 00:09:45,360
area has a higher probability of success.
 
When price is trading in the Discount area,  

106
00:09:45,360 --> 00:09:50,680
there's a higher probability that price 
will reverse and start moving higher. 

107
00:09:50,680 --> 00:09:56,440
This means that buying in the Discount 
area has a higher probability of success.
  

108
00:09:56,440 --> 00:10:01,920
Of course, you won’t use the Premium and 
Discount zones as a standalone strategy. 

109
00:10:01,920 --> 00:10:06,400
But by combining them with the other 
concepts, you can start to build a more  

110
00:10:06,400 --> 00:10:10,480
complete picture of the market.
In this smart money approach,  

111
00:10:10,480 --> 00:10:16,360
you will use the Premium and Discount concept 
to help you decide when to enter a trade. 
  

112
00:10:16,360 --> 00:10:21,920
For example, if you're looking to go long, 
you might wait for price to pull back into  

113
00:10:21,920 --> 00:10:26,600
a Discount area before entering.
If you're looking to go short,  

114
00:10:26,600 --> 00:10:31,480
you might wait for price to rally 
into a Premium area before entering. 
  

115
00:10:31,480 --> 00:10:34,280
Supply/demand
Supply and demand zones are  

116
00:10:34,280 --> 00:10:40,360
one of the most important smart money concepts.
When smart money want to open a position with a  

117
00:10:40,360 --> 00:10:45,400
large volume, they can't just randomly 
place a huge order in the market. 

118
00:10:45,400 --> 00:10:51,800
This would upset the balance of supply and demand, 
and trigger their order at a worse price. This  

119
00:10:51,800 --> 00:10:58,720
could seriously eat into their potential profits.
 
Instead, banks split their large positions into  

120
00:10:58,720 --> 00:11:04,760
smaller, more manageable blocks and place 
them at strategic levels in the market. 

121
00:11:04,760 --> 00:11:08,200
These levels are known as 
supply and demand zones.
  

122
00:11:08,200 --> 00:11:15,680
A demand zone is located at the last down candle 
or series of down candles before price makes a  

123
00:11:15,680 --> 00:11:22,320
big move upwards. This is where the big players 
are secretly accumulating their long positions,  

124
00:11:22,320 --> 00:11:28,440
hoping to ride the wave of bullish momentum.
When price comes back down to this demand zone,  

125
00:11:28,440 --> 00:11:34,720
you often see a strong reaction. That's why 
demand zones act as strong support levels,  

126
00:11:34,720 --> 00:11:41,040
where price is likely to bounce higher.
 
A supply zone is located at the last up  

127
00:11:41,040 --> 00:11:46,000
candle or series of up candles 
before price makes a big move  

128
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:51,520
downwards. This is where the big players 
are quietly unloading their positions,  

129
00:11:51,520 --> 00:11:57,960
hoping to profit from a potential price drop.
Supply zones act as strong resistance levels,  

130
00:11:57,960 --> 00:12:01,840
where price is likely to 
stall or even reverse lower.
  

131
00:12:01,840 --> 00:12:04,320
Mitigation
In smart money jargon,  

132
00:12:04,320 --> 00:12:10,640
you’ll often hear the word “mitigation”. This 
term is related to supply and demand zones. 

133
00:12:10,640 --> 00:12:15,480
Now, in this price chart, observe 
this new Demand zone forming. 

134
00:12:15,480 --> 00:12:22,440
Price started to rally higher from this zone. 
This is what we call an Unmitigated Demand zone.
  

135
00:12:22,440 --> 00:12:29,560
An Unmitigated zone is like a magnet for price. 
It's an area that hasn't been visited before,  

136
00:12:29,560 --> 00:12:33,640
and it's screaming out for attention.
The big players who placed their  

137
00:12:33,640 --> 00:12:39,600
orders here are eagerly waiting for 
price to come back and fill them.
  

138
00:12:39,600 --> 00:12:45,560
On the flip side, here we see a Supply zone 
with a reaction. Price has come back to  

139
00:12:45,560 --> 00:12:52,480
this level, touched it, and then fallen away.
This is what we call a Mitigated Supply zone. 

140
00:12:52,480 --> 00:12:56,920
A Mitigated zone is an area 
that has been visited before. 

141
00:12:56,920 --> 00:13:03,200
The sellers that placed their sell orders at this 
level have already had their fill, and they're  

142
00:13:03,200 --> 00:13:08,880
probably not interested in sticking around.
 
This is important because knowing whether a  

143
00:13:08,880 --> 00:13:15,960
zone is Mitigated or Unmitigated can give you 
clues about what price is likely to do next. 

144
00:13:15,960 --> 00:13:21,320
If you see price approaching an Unmitigated 
Demand zone, you know that there are probably  

145
00:13:21,320 --> 00:13:27,440
a lot of unfilled buy orders waiting there.
This means that there's a good chance price will  

146
00:13:27,440 --> 00:13:34,000
bounce off this level and start rallying higher.
 
On the other hand, if you see price approaching a  

147
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:40,560
Mitigated Supply zone, you know that most of the 
sell orders have probably already been filled. 

148
00:13:40,560 --> 00:13:46,760
This means that there's less resistance at this 
level, and price may be able to break through  

149
00:13:46,760 --> 00:13:50,504
and continue falling.
 
 
Fair value gaps 

150
00:13:50,504 --> 00:13:54,960
Fair value gaps are used to detect 
market imbalances or inefficiencies.  

151
00:13:54,960 --> 00:13:59,040
These imbalances happen when there is 
significant buying or selling pressure. 

152
00:14:00,320 --> 00:14:06,120
When you look at a chart, you'll notice that 
most of the time, the price tends to retrace  

153
00:14:06,120 --> 00:14:11,720
and leave wicks on both sides of the candles.
 
However, sometimes you can see candles with  

154
00:14:11,720 --> 00:14:17,400
no overlap on either side, which 
is what we call a fair value gap. 

155
00:14:17,400 --> 00:14:22,840
The idea behind fair value gaps is that the 
market will eventually come back to these  

156
00:14:22,840 --> 00:14:28,640
inefficiencies, before continuing in the 
same direction as the initial strong move. 

157
00:14:28,640 --> 00:14:32,680
This is similar to the principle 
of supply and demand trading.
  

158
00:14:32,680 --> 00:14:38,920
For a fair value gap to develop, there must be 
a set of three candles characterized by heavy  

159
00:14:38,920 --> 00:14:44,880
buying or selling in the same direction.
A gap will form between the first candle's  

160
00:14:44,880 --> 00:14:52,400
higher wick and the last candle's lower wick.
 
In this example, the price movement doesn't  

161
00:14:52,400 --> 00:14:56,960
have a Fair Value Gap, as the 
previous candle's high level  

162
00:14:56,960 --> 00:15:05,138
balances out the low level of the third candle.
This price action is considered to be balanced.
  

163
00:15:05,138 --> 00:15:06,640
Liquidity & Inducement
Next we need to talk about  

164
00:15:06,640 --> 00:15:11,040
liquidity and inducement.
In simple terms, liquidity  

165
00:15:11,040 --> 00:15:15,480
is just another word for money.
Liquidity refers to the amount of  

166
00:15:15,480 --> 00:15:21,440
money flowing in and out of the market.
 
Now, where does this money come from? It  

167
00:15:21,440 --> 00:15:27,280
comes from orders placed by traders.
And the big banks and institutions are  

168
00:15:27,280 --> 00:15:31,320
paying close attention to where 
these orders are coming from. 

169
00:15:31,320 --> 00:15:35,120
You see, banks use a simple 
strategy called inducement,  

170
00:15:35,120 --> 00:15:42,320
to lure unsuspecting traders into their traps. 
 
They'll create artificial setups in the market,  

171
00:15:42,320 --> 00:15:46,760
making it look like there's a lot 
of demand for a particular market. 

172
00:15:46,760 --> 00:15:51,280
And they do this by placing a 
bunch of orders in a specific area,  

173
00:15:51,280 --> 00:15:57,120
creating what's known as a liquidity pool.
They want to induce traders to activate their  

174
00:15:57,120 --> 00:16:02,320
capital. In other words, they want you 
to place your orders in the same area,  

175
00:16:02,320 --> 00:16:06,000
so they can take your money!
 
Once the banks have lured in  

176
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:11,160
enough orders, they'll make their move.
They'll start buying or selling in the  

177
00:16:11,160 --> 00:16:17,600
opposite direction, taking out all the stop 
losses and freeing up positions for themselves. 
  

178
00:16:17,600 --> 00:16:23,120
The banks don't want to fight for every move 
they make. They want to be able to initiate  

179
00:16:23,120 --> 00:16:28,920
price in the direction they want, without 
hitting any areas that could cause a battle. 

180
00:16:29,640 --> 00:16:33,520
That's why they build these 
liquidity areas in the first place. 

181
00:16:33,520 --> 00:16:38,680
By inducing one side of the market 
and then clearing out that liquidity,  

182
00:16:38,680 --> 00:16:43,800
the banks give themselves all the buying 
or selling power they need to move price  

183
00:16:43,800 --> 00:16:48,680
wherever they want it to go. 
 
Let’s consider a trading range. 

184
00:16:48,680 --> 00:16:54,680
Below the support level, there are stop-loss 
orders of buyers, and above the resistance  

185
00:16:54,680 --> 00:17:01,360
level, there are stop-loss orders of sellers.
When the market breaks below the support level,  

186
00:17:01,360 --> 00:17:07,400
new sell trades are triggered by traders 
expecting a continuation of the breakout. 

187
00:17:07,400 --> 00:17:12,120
A break above the resistance 
level activates new “buy” trades.
  

188
00:17:12,120 --> 00:17:17,040
So liquidity refers to the orders 
on both sides of the trading range. 

189
00:17:17,040 --> 00:17:22,360
Buy-side liquidity represents new buy 
orders above the resistance level,  

190
00:17:22,360 --> 00:17:28,960
accompanied by stop-loss orders of sellers.
Sell-side liquidity is characterized by  

191
00:17:28,960 --> 00:17:35,760
stop-loss orders of buyers below the support 
level, accompanied by new sell orders. 

192
00:17:35,760 --> 00:17:39,400
By pushing the market above 
these levels, smart money can  

193
00:17:39,400 --> 00:17:46,280
access the liquidity required to move price.
 
 
So, where else can you find liquidity? The obvious  

194
00:17:46,280 --> 00:17:52,880
place to look is at previous swing highs and lows.
These are areas where the market has reversed in  

195
00:17:52,880 --> 00:17:58,240
the past, and they're often seen as 
key levels of support and resistance. 

196
00:17:58,240 --> 00:18:04,000
Think about it like this. If the market has 
bounced off a certain price level multiple times  

197
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:09,920
in the past, there's a good chance that there 
are a lot of orders sitting at that level. 
  

198
00:18:09,920 --> 00:18:14,920
Another place to look for liquidity 
is at equal highs and equal lows. 

199
00:18:14,920 --> 00:18:19,800
These are areas where the price has 
reached the same level multiple times,  

200
00:18:19,800 --> 00:18:25,040
creating a sort of "line in the sand" 
that traders are watching closely. 

201
00:18:25,040 --> 00:18:31,800
If the price breaks through an equal high or low, 
it could trigger a wave of pending orders and stop  

202
00:18:31,800 --> 00:18:39,680
losses. That's why these levels are often seen 
as key battlegrounds between buyers and sellers.
  

203
00:18:39,680 --> 00:18:44,480
Trend lines are another great place to 
look for liquidity. These are diagonal  

204
00:18:44,480 --> 00:18:51,280
lines that connect a series of highs or lows.
If the price is bouncing off a trend line, there's  

205
00:18:51,280 --> 00:18:57,720
a good chance that there are a lot of pending 
orders sitting just above or below that line. 
  

206
00:18:57,720 --> 00:19:03,360
Chart patterns are another key area to 
watch for liquidity. These are specific  

207
00:19:03,360 --> 00:19:09,400
formations that the price makes on the chart.
Each of these patterns has its own unique  

208
00:19:09,400 --> 00:19:15,760
characteristics, but they all have one thing in 
common: they're often seen as key levels where  

209
00:19:15,760 --> 00:19:22,280
the market is likely to break out or reverse.
And where there's a potential for a big move,  

210
00:19:22,280 --> 00:19:26,160
there's usually a lot of 
liquidity sitting nearby.
  

211
00:19:26,160 --> 00:19:39,120
If this smart money guide helped you, 
you don’t want to miss the next ones!

